The CPU (Central Processing Unit) is the brain of your computer, responsible for executing most instructions that your computer receives. It's the primary component that performs calculations, makes decisions, and controls the other components of your computer.

----

The GPU (Graphics Processing Unit) is a type of microprocessor designed specifically for handling the complex calculations and rendering of images and graphics in computers, laptops, and mobile devices. It's responsible for rendering 2D and 3D graphics, video games, and other graphical content.

---

A motherboard is the main circuit board of a computer that connects and supports all the hardware components together. It's often referred to as the "mainboard" or "moboard." The motherboard serves as a communication pathway, allowing the various components to exchange data and instructions.

---

The Power Supply Unit (PSU) is a crucial component in your computer system, responsible for providing power to all the components inside the system. It's like the "heart" of your computer, pumping life-giving power to every component.

---

The storage system in your computer is responsible for storing and retrieving data, programs, and operating systems. There are two primary types of storage devices: Hard Disk Drives (HDDs) and Solid-State Drives (SSDs).

---

The cooling system in a PC, also known as the thermal management system, is responsible for dissipating heat generated by the components inside the computer, such as the CPU, GPU, and motherboard. A proper cooling system helps to prevent overheating, which can damage the components and reduce their performance.

---

In a PC (Personal Computer), the case, also known as the chassis or tower, is the outer casing that houses all the internal components of the computer. It provides a protective enclosure for the hardware and helps to keep it organized and easily accessible. 

---

RAM (Random Access Memory) is a type of computer storage that temporarily holds data and applications while a computer is running. It's a crucial component of a computer system, allowing for fast access to frequently-used information and enabling the computer to perform tasks efficiently.